The `qeubo/` subdirectory
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Derived from qEUBO (the q-Expected Utility of Best Option preference-
based optimization library), distributed under the MIT License.
See the file `qeubo/LICENSE` for the full text and copyright
attribution from the upstream qEUBO project.

The MIT License requires that this attribution and the license text
itself be preserved in any redistribution of the derivative work.
Downstream packagers and redistributors must include `qeubo/LICENSE`
alongside any binary or source form of the `qeubo` module.

The MIT scope is the **whole** `qeubo/` directory tree, including:

  - `qeubo/vendor/`, the unmodified upstream qEUBO source.
  - `qeubo/runtime/`, the LLM-derived wrapper code adapted from the
    project author's prototype at
    `~/preference_optimizer/qEUBO/wss3/{service,storage}.py`.
    The prototype was authored by an LLM with full visibility into
    qEUBO source, which makes it MIT-derivative under the
    conservative interpretation; anything we adapt from it inherits
    that status.
  - `qeubo/__init__.py`, `qeubo/README.md`, `qeubo/LICENSE`.

upstream qEUBO project: https://github.com/facebookresearch/qEUBO
upstream MIT license: see `qeubo/LICENSE`

Derivation provenance
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The vendored library at `qeubo/vendor/src/` was copied from the
upstream qEUBO source tree at the project author's working copy
(`~/preference_optimizer/qEUBO/src/`). No modifications to the
vendored source: the library is bit-for-bit identical to upstream
modulo the `__pycache__` directories, which were stripped at copy
time as a hygiene measure.

The runtime wrapper at `qeubo/runtime/` was adapted from
`~/preference_optimizer/qEUBO/wss3/{service,storage}.py`, with the
following deletions per the qEUBO integration dispatch's PBO-core
scope:

  - All references to the colormap / gradient-optimizer extensions
    that the wss3 prototype carried for an unrelated colormap-tuning
    use case: `colormap.py` imports, `_compute_colour_data`,
    `_attach_colour_data`, and the `colour_table_*` / `*_jab` fields
    in pair / best responses.
  - The gradient-specific config fields in `_DEFAULT_CONFIG`:
    `n_waypoints`, `colour_table_size`, `hue_global`,
    `hue_sweep_limit`, `endpoint_chroma_bound`,
    `interior_chroma_bound`. Only the PBO-core fields remain.
  - The WebSocket dispatcher (`server.py`) is not vendored at all;
    REST route handlers in `backend/api/routes/qeubo.py` replace
    its function.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
The licensing boundary at the import surface
------------------------------------------------------------------------

Code outside `backend/qeubo/` (notably the FastAPI route handlers
and any sibling encode/decode utility modules under
`backend/api/routes/`) is public domain. Such code consumes the
qeubo package via the documented public API in
`backend/qeubo/README.md`, not by reading the source files in
`vendor/` or `runtime/`. Source visibility tainted with MIT-
derivative status would carry the MIT obligation outward; calling
documented function signatures (a non-copyrightable interface)
does not. This is the "intermediary preserves obligations" pattern
documented in the qEUBO integration dispatch.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Practical implications for downstream users
------------------------------------------------------------------------

If you redistribute the LengYue backend in source form: include
`qeubo/LICENSE` and this NOTICE file. No further obligations.

If you redistribute compiled artifacts that include the `qeubo`
module: include `qeubo/LICENSE` alongside the binary. The MIT
attribution requirement applies to that module specifically.

If you redistribute compiled artifacts WITHOUT `qeubo` (the
optimisation feature is gated behind the `QEUBO_ENABLED`
configuration flag and can be excluded from a deployed build):
no licensing obligations apply. The remainder of the backend is
in the public domain.
